%I A396324 #7 Jun 12 2026 17:35:27
%S A396324 8,9,16,25,27,32,36,40,48,49,63,64,72,80,81,96,98,100,104,108,112,117,
%T A396324 121,125,128,136,144,160,169,171,176,189,192,196,200,208,216,224,225,
%U A396324 232,243,252,256,272,275,279,288,289,296,304,320,324,328,333,343,351
%N A396324 Numbers k for which there exists a residue class r (mod k) with s = r+m*k, m >= 0, such that rad(s) | gcd(s,k), where rad = A007947.
%C A396324 Squarefree k are such that rad(k) | s implies k | s, thus do not appear in this sequence.
%C A396324 Superset of A246547 / {4} (proper prime powers), superset of A303606 (perfect powers of squarefree composites), thus, superset of their union, A072777 / {4}.
%C A396324 Intersects A059404 and its proper subsets A332785 (e.g., a(9) = 40), A052486 (Achilles, e.g., a(14) = 72), A386762 (e.g., a(28) = 144), and A383394 (e.g., a(702) = 5184).
%C A396324 Conjecture: A359280 is a proper subset (and thus, all powerful numbers greater than 4, i.e., A001694 \ {1, 4} = A359280 U A072777 / {4}).
%C A396324 Does not meet A366825, since for k in A366825, k = lpf(k)*rad(k). Therefore, since lpf(k)*rad(k) is the smallest number that exceeds rad(k), then all r < k such that rad(k) | r (i.e., rad(k) itself) also divide k.
%C A396324 Proper subset of A393869 (numbers k such that A053669(k) < A003557(k)).
%H A396324 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A396324/b396324.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A396324 Let r = rad(a(n)) and m = A381803(n).
%e A396324 Table of n, a(n), r, m, and k for select n:
%e A396324     n    a(n)    r    m   k
%e A396324   ----------------------------------------------------
%e A396324     1      8     2    1   {6}
%e A396324     2      9     3    1   {6}
%e A396324     3     16     2    4   {6, 10, 12, 14}
%e A396324     4     25     5    3   {10, 15, 20}
%e A396324     7     36     6    1   {30}
%e A396324     8     40    10    1   {30}
%e A396324    13     72     6    4   {30, 42, 60, 66}
%e A396324    18    100    10    3   {30, 70, 90}
%e A396324    27    144     6   13   {30, 42, 60, 66, 78, 84, 90, 102, 114, 120, 126, 132, 138}
%e A396324    42    252    42    1   {210}
%e A396324   457   3276   546    1   {2730}
%e A396324   701   5184     6  805   {30, 42, 60, 66, ..., 5178}
%e A396324 The number 4 is not a term since 1 and 3 are coprime to 4, and 2 | 4.
%e A396324 a(1) = 8 since r = 6 is such that s = 6 + 8*m, m >= 0, is even, yet not divisible by 8.
%e A396324 a(2) = 9 since r = 6 is such that s = 6 + 9*m, m >= 0, is divisible by 3 but not by 9.
%e A396324 The number k = 12 is not in the sequence since, though there exists r = 10 with s = 10 + 12*m such that rad(s) does not divide 12, gcd(s,12) = 2; s is not divisible by 3.
%e A396324 a(3) = 16 since r in {6, 10, 12, 14} are such that s = r + 16*m, m >= 0, are even but not divisible by 16.
%e A396324 The number 36 is a term, since there exists one residue class r = 30 with s = 30 + 36*m, m >= 0, such that both rad(36) | gcd(s,36) and rad(s) does not divide 36. Examples: 66 = 2*3*11, 112 = 2*3*17, 138 = 2*3*23, etc.
%e A396324 a(9) = 48 since there exists one residue class r in {30 = 6*5, 42 = 6*7} with s = 30 + 48*m such that both rad(36) | gcd(s,36) and rad(s) does not divide 36. Examples: 66 = 2*3*11, 112 = 2*3*17, 138 = 2*3*23, etc.
%e A396324 The number 45 is not a term since, though for r = 30, 1 < gcd(30,45) < 30, s = 30 + 45 = 75 is divisible by rad(45) = 15.
%t A396324 Select[
%t A396324   Select[Range[360], Not @* SquareFreeQ],
%t A396324   Function[k, r = rad[k];
%t A396324     s = Select[Range[k], CoprimeQ[#, k] &];
%t A396324     t = Union@ Flatten@ Mod[TensorProduct @@
%t A396324       Map[(p = #; NestWhileList[Mod[p*#, k] &, 1, UnsameQ, All]) &,
%t A396324        FactorInteger[k][[All, 1]] ], k];
%t A396324     Count[Complement[Range[0, k - 1], Union[s, t]],
%t A396324       _?(Divisible[#, r] &)] > 0] ]
%Y A396324 Cf. A003557, A005117, A007947, A013929, A024619, A052486, A053669, A059404, A246547, A303606, A359280, A366825, A381803, A383384, A386762, A393869.
%K A396324 nonn
%O A396324 1,1
